<h4>
    What is a system?
</h4>

<p>
    In many different parts of physics,
    we consider a "system."
    These facts are important to know about a system:
</p>

<ul class = 'principleList'>
    <li>
        When physicists use the word 'system,' it means we are analyzing
        multiple objects as though they are a single whole.
    </li>
    <li>
        A system is a theoretical construct.
        This means, it is not something your can touch or feel,
        it is a way of mathematically analyzing objects.
        It does not really exist, except in our own analysis.
        Similarly, if we say "Johnny has five apples,"
        the apples actually exist in the real world
        but the number "five" is only a human way of analyzing the apples.
        "Systems" are the same.
    </li>
    <li>
        An object can be in a system or not in the same problem,
        and this simply means you are analyzing it differently.
        For example, imagine I am doing some physics about a Mars Rover
        driving on Mars.
        In one sentence, I might write "The Rover-Mars system,"
        but in the next sentence, I write "The Rover system."
        If so, this is intentional, and I mean something different in each sentence.
    </li>
    <li>
        The most famous example of a system is the Solar Sytem.
    </li>
</ul>

