<h4>
    How to discuss gravitational potential energy:
</h4>

<ul class = 'principleList'>
    <li>
        Gravitational Potential Energy is the
        <emph>potential</emph> to begin moving
        as a result of gravity.
    </li>
    <li>
        Because gravity only exists if two obejcts attract
        each other, gravitational potential energy
        also exists only if two objects attract each other.
    </li>
    <li>
        No individual object can have gravitational potential energy,
        but only a system of two objects can.
    </li>
</ul>

<h5>
    In space:
</h5>
<p>
    Imagine small two objects close to each other and stationary
    in outer space.
    According to Newton's Theory of Universal Gravitation,
    because both objects have mass, they must be attracted
    by the force of gravity.
    Thus, there must be some gravitation potential energy,
    as the two objects have the <emph>potential</emph>
    to begin moving.
</p>
<p>
    However, which object has the gravitational potential energy?
    Suppose the objects are a table and a chair.
    The table alone, were it not for the chair,
    would not have any gravitation potential energy.
    The chair alone, were it not for the table,
    would not have any gravitational potential energy.
    Thus, neither the table or the chair can have gravitational potential energy.
</p>

<p>
    Therefore, the only correct thing to say is
    that the <strong>table-chair system</strong> has gravitational potential energy.
</p>

<h5>
    On earth:
</h5>
<p>
    All objects on earth are attracted towards the center of the earth
    due to gravity.
    Consider one example: a ball high up on the air.
    The ball is attracted towards the earth due to gravity.
    Therefore, it has gravitational potential energy, because it has the potential
    to start falling down towards the earth.
    But it can't have this energy alone, becuase gravity is an attraction between
    the ball and the earth.
    So we write that the "ball-earth system" has gravitational potential energy.
</p>

<p>
    Imagine you are on the fourth floor of a building.
    Typically, someone would say "You have gravitational potential energy."
    But this is not correct.
    What we call "gravity" here on earth
    is a mutual attraction between a person and the earth.
    It exists only if both the person and the earth are present.
    Therefore, it is incorrect to say that a person has gravitational
    potential energy.
    You must say that the <strong>person-earth system</strong> has gravitational potential energy.
</p>



